Class Bundle

java.lang.Object
  sailpoint.tools.xml.AbstractXmlObject

All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, Certifiable, Describable, RoleContainer, sailpoint.tools.xml.PersistentXmlObject, sailpoint.tools.xml.XMLReferenceTarget
public class Bundle
extends AbstractCertifiableEntity
implements Certifiable, java.lang.Cloneable, RoleContainer, Describable

A class used to represent roles. The class name is Bundle for historical reasons (representing bundles of entitlements). You can assume that "bundle" is synonymous with "role" throughout the model.

Field Detail

ATT_MERGE_TEMPLATES

public static final java.lang.String ATT_MERGE_TEMPLATES
The name of an attribute that can appear in the Attributes map that indicates that the Template list (provisioning policies) should be MERGED with the profiles rather than replacing the profiles.

This is the first time the Bundle attributes map has been used for system properties, but it eliminages the need to add Hibernate columns for things that will never be queried.

See Also:
Constant Field Values

ATT_DUPLICATE_ACCOUNTS

public static final java.lang.String ATT_DUPLICATE_ACCOUNTS
The name of an attribute in the Attributes map that indicates this role supports provisioning to multiple accounts on the same Application. This triggers more complex role expansion in the plan compiler, and a more complex account selection UI that allows you to select different accounts for each required IT role. This is only relevant for assignable (typically type=business) roles.

getPermits

public java.util.List<Bundle> getPermits()
List of permitted roles. This is normally used with "business" roles to reference "IT" roles as a way of indicating which IT roles are allowed to support a business role. Note that this is NOT the same thing as inheritance. Business and IT roles can have independent inheritance hierarchies.

getRequirements

public java.util.List<Bundle> getRequirements()
List of required roles. This is normally used with "business" roles to reference "IT" roles as a way of indicating which IT roles are required to support a business role.

The distinction between the required and permits list is subtle and useful mostly for outbound provisioning. It is a statement that in order to have a certain business role you must have a set of IT roles and in addition other IT roles are permitted but optional.

For certification and reporting this distinction is not that important. The required and permits list are merged to form the "allowed" list of IT roles.

This flag allows the Certificationer to skip the differencing step.
